Here is a first-pass Beast2 comms design aimed at fault tolerance, with wings as the delivery reward layer rather than halos.

The core idea is simple:

Do not assume the network is alive. Do not assume the route exists. Do not assume a central server will answer.
Instead, every node is a possible courier, every message is a durable artifact, and every transport is opportunistic.

System shape

Think of Beast Comms as five layers:

1. Identity and trust
Each device has a persistent Beast identity keypair.
Users can have human identities mapped to several devices.
	•	person identity: Michael
	•	device identities: phone, laptop, village hub, family tablet
	•	trust graph: family, village, friends, subscribed hubs, known relays

Messages are signed by sender identity.
Payloads can be end-to-end encrypted to intended recipients.
Relays can carry them without reading them.

2. Postal artifact format
Everything becomes a Beast artifact:
	•	message
	•	photo
	•	file
	•	voice note
	•	generator
	•	encyclopedia shard
	•	routing update
	•	delivery receipt

Each artifact has:
	•	content hash
	•	sender id
	•	recipient scope
	•	priority
	•	size
	•	expiration / retention policy
	•	redundancy target
	•	routing hints
	•	delivery status metadata

This fits Beast2 naturally: artifacts persist, are hash-addressed, deduplicate cleanly, and can be re-forwarded safely.

3. Multi-transport delivery fabric
Messages can move over any available transport:
	•	direct internet peer connection
	•	relayed internet connection
	•	local Wi-Fi / LAN
	•	Wi-Fi Direct
	•	Bluetooth / BLE
	•	tethered device bridge
	•	sneakernet sync when devices come near each other
	•	village hub sync
	•	satellite or long-range link later if ever added

The system does not care which path is used.
It cares only that a courier moved the artifact closer to where it belongs.

4. Store-and-forward routing
Nodes do not merely connect; they carry mail.

A node may hold:
	•	mail for itself
	•	mail for local cluster
	•	mail for adjacent villages
	•	global cached public artifacts
	•	queued outbound mail waiting for any viable path

This is postal logic, not fragile socket logic.

5. Reward layer: wings
Wings symbolize movement, delivery, and service to the network.

Not "I computed hard."
Not "I spammed packets."
But: I helped communication move.

Examples:
	•	carried village mail to a hub
	•	hosted a stable always-on post office
	•	delivered bundles across a partition
	•	maintained trusted address books / route summaries
	•	served as a bridge between two clusters
	•	preserved mail during outage until route restored

That is much harder to fake than generic engagement points, if designed carefully.

⸻

Fault-tolerance principles

These should be explicit Beast axioms for comms:

Axiom 1: Every message expects failure

A message should survive:
	•	sender going offline
	•	receiver going offline
	•	relay disappearing
	•	IP address changes
	•	temporary split-brain networks
	•	duplicate delivery attempts
	•	reorder
	•	retransmission

Axiom 2: Delivery is eventual, not fragile

Do not promise "live connection."
Promise:
	•	queued
	•	carried
	•	reached village
	•	reached recipient cluster
	•	decrypted by recipient device
	•	acknowledged

That is more honest and more robust.

Axiom 3: Redundancy should match reality

When internet is stable, use low redundancy.
When links are unstable or war/disaster mode is detected, raise redundancy automatically.

Axiom 4: Locality matters

A device in or near a village should preferentially preload or retain village mail.
This is your "intelligently loaded local mail" idea.

Axiom 5: Couriers are first-class citizens

Relays and hubs are not invisible plumbing.
They are part of the social architecture of the network.

⸻

Data model

A message bundle might look conceptually like this:

b2_artifact_type message_bundle
b2_bundle_hash H(...)
b2_sender_id person:granddaughter
b2_recipient_scope household:grandparents
b2_encryption e2ee
b2_priority family_high
b2_created_at 2026-04-15T22:11:00Z
b2_expire_at 2026-05-15T22:11:00Z
b2_redundancy_target 3
b2_locality_hint village:khaneh_red
b2_transport_hint internet mesh bluetooth wifi_direct
b2_payload_refs
  message_text_hash ...
  photo_hash ...
b2_ack_policy recipient_ack
b2_forward_policy store_and_forward

Large payloads should be chunked and content-addressed.
That gives resumability and deduplication almost for free.

⸻

Routing model

Use a hybrid approach, because pure elegance usually loses to real networks.

Routing tiers

Tier A: direct delivery

If recipient is online and reachable:
	•	send directly
	•	receive ack
	•	done

Tier B: assisted direct delivery

Use rendezvous / introducer / hole punching:
	•	a known hub or introducer helps peers discover each other
	•	attempt NAT traversal
	•	if direct path succeeds, switch to p2p

Tier C: trusted relay delivery

If direct connection fails:
	•	encrypted message passes through one or more relays
	•	relays cannot read it, but can store and forward it

Tier D: locality cache delivery

If recipient cluster is offline:
	•	store mail at nearest trusted locality hub or courier set
	•	when someone from recipient locality appears, sync opportunistically

Tier E: physical / opportunistic mesh

If internet path is absent:
	•	carry by nearby phones, hubs, travelers, vehicles, etc.
	•	eventual sync when path emerges

That last one is where the network becomes genuinely resilient.

⸻

Wings reward design

The reward system should celebrate movement and reliability, not volume.

Why wings

Halo implies virtue in a vague moral sense.
Wings imply:
	•	motion
	•	carrying
	•	bridging distance
	•	service between places

It is visually and conceptually correct.

Types of wings

Courier Wings
Earned for successful forwarding of mail toward destinations.

Postmaster Wings
Earned for running stable hubs, maintaining uptime, serving cached mail reliably.

Bridge Wings
Earned when a node meaningfully connects otherwise separated clusters.

Storm Wings
Earned for successful carriage during outages, degraded networks, or emergency mode.

Memory Wings
Earned for preserving important public artifacts, directory shards, and address books.

Anti-gaming principles

Do not reward:
	•	raw bytes forwarded
	•	raw message count
	•	self-sent loops
	•	repeated duplicate forwarding
	•	spam relays
	•	easy same-room churn

Instead reward:
	•	unique useful deliveries
	•	path-shortening contribution
	•	successful custody transfer
	•	persistence over time
	•	delivery under adversity
	•	validated bridge service between distinct trust/locality zones

A relay only gets credit when its participation was actually needed.

Wings accounting

Each artifact can carry a limited "reward budget" split across contributing nodes.
For example:
	•	sender funds a tiny voluntary reward
	•	recipient or community fund can add more
	•	network grants emergency bonus in outage mode

Credit is split by actual contribution:
	•	hub that stored it for 6 days during outage
	•	courier phone that carried it into village
	•	local handset that delivered to recipient

This prevents infinite minting.

⸻

System modes

The system should adapt behavior based on observed conditions.

1. Optimistic mode

Assume internet mostly works.
	•	low redundancy
	•	prefer direct routes
	•	use hubs for efficiency
	•	smaller cache windows
	•	quick pruning

2. Partition mode

Assume clusters may be cut off for hours or days.
	•	higher redundancy
	•	retain address/routing summaries longer
	•	preload locality mail
	•	encourage multi-hop custody copies

3. Crisis mode

Assume regional outage or intentional shutdown.
	•	maximum store-and-forward
	•	prioritize family, emergency, and directory messages
	•	compress aggressively
	•	preserve power
	•	allow delayed batched sync
	•	reward bridging strongly

⸻

UX example 1: "Post office" setup

This is the optimistic, internet-mostly-up case.

A person in a town has a mini PC, router-attached box, old laptop, or always-on desktop. They open Beast and set up a Post Office.

What they see

Screen: Create Local Post Office

"Turn this device into a trusted mail hub for your home, block, building, or village."

Options:
	•	Hub name: Oak Street Post Office
	•	Service area: Oak Street / nearby homes
	•	Reliability mode: Optimistic
	•	Reserve storage for mail: 200 GB
	•	Keep local directory cache: On
	•	Serve public artifact cache: Optional
	•	Allow NAT assist for trusted contacts: On
	•	Backup power available: No
	•	Reward type shown publicly: Postmaster Wings

Then Beast gives a plain-language summary:

This hub will store mail for nearby people, help devices find each other, and keep delivery moving when someone is temporarily offline.

User taps Start Post Office.

What happens under the hood

The hub:
	•	gets a stable Beast node id
	•	publishes signed reachability summaries
	•	maintains local trust and directory shards
	•	acts as introducer for direct p2p attempts
	•	caches local outbound and inbound mail
	•	keeps minimal route summaries for known localities
	•	optionally mirrors public Beast artifacts

UX flow in practice

A granddaughter sends:
	•	text
	•	photo
	•	short voice note

Recipient grandparents are offline.

The system UI for sender says:

Sending to Grandparents
	•	Sent to Oak Street Post Office
	•	Waiting for village delivery window
	•	2 trusted routes available

Later, someone travels through village or a handset comes online there.
Hub sync occurs. Grandparents’ handhelds light up:

New Beast Comms
	•	Message and photo from your granddaughter
	•	Delivered via Oak Street Post Office and 1 local courier

That last line quietly teaches the user how resilience works.

Why this mode is efficient

Because internet mostly stays up:
	•	one or two hubs can handle directory, rendezvous, and buffering
	•	redundancy stays low
	•	bandwidth is used intelligently
	•	smartphones don’t need giant routing state
	•	most traffic is direct or hub-assisted

Failure handling

If the hub goes down:
	•	clients fail over to cached secondary hub list
	•	recent mail bundles remain on sender devices until custody is confirmed elsewhere
	•	address books and trust lists are replicated in tiny signed snapshots
	•	nearby devices can promote a temporary replacement hub

That is important: a post office is a convenience, not a single point of failure.

⸻

UX example 2: Pure mesh village mode

Now assume a town or village where there is no dependable hub.
Smartphones are the main compute/storage.
Each phone may contribute up to 16 GB for routing state, mail custody, caches, and address/directory data.

This is harsher, but very possible if you design for it.

What users see

A person opens Beast Comms and sees:

Village Mesh Active
	•	Internet: unstable
	•	Nearby Beast devices: 11
	•	Local couriers available: 4
	•	Mail queue health: good
	•	Your phone is carrying 23 undelivered items for nearby households

There is a button:

Review Carried Mail

Tapping it does not reveal contents. It shows only categories:
	•	5 family messages
	•	2 photos
	•	11 public directory updates
	•	5 encyclopedia fragments

And:
	•	Estimated storage used: 1.8 GB
	•	Your current courier status: Bridge Wings I

This keeps the user aware without compromising privacy.

Pure mesh routing behavior

Phones exchange:
	•	signed neighborhood summaries
	•	recent custody receipts
	•	compressed "who can reach whom" bloom filters or shard summaries
	•	local address books for trusted communities
	•	chunk availability maps
	•	battery / willingness / storage contribution state

When two phones meet:
	1.	authenticate as Beast nodes
	2.	compare missing summaries
	3.	exchange higher-priority undelivered mail
	4.	transfer chunks opportunistically
	5.	update custody and reward logs
	6.	part ways

No central server required.

Storage budget within 16 GB

A rough conceptual split on a 512 GB phone that donates up to 16 GB:
	•	2 GB routing and directory summaries
	•	6 GB private and local-forwarded message bundles
	•	4 GB chunk cache for large payloads
	•	2 GB public emergency / encyclopedia shards
	•	2 GB redundancy / overflow / delayed cleanup

In practice, routing summaries should be much smaller than raw "all IPs and MACs."
You do not want one global flat table.
You want compressed locality-aware summaries and trust-scoped directories.

That means:
	•	village clusters
	•	route likelihoods
	•	last-seen windows
	•	custody maps
	•	contact group summaries
	•	optional DHT-like shard indices where needed

UX flow in practice

A man bicycles back from the city.

While near a better-connected zone, his phone picks up:
	•	family mail for his village
	•	pending public notices
	•	a few artifact chunks requested by local devices

He does not do anything manually.

When he nears the village:
	•	his phone detects familiar Beast identities nearby
	•	sync windows open automatically
	•	grandparents’ devices light up
	•	several other homes get queued deliveries

His UI says:

Courier Run Complete
	•	14 items reached your village
	•	9 delivered
	•	5 handed to nearby couriers
	•	You earned 31 Wings
	•	Storm multiplier applied: intermittent partition

That is a good Beast moment. The system is legible, rewarding, and alive.

Why this mode is fault tolerant

Because delivery does not depend on:
	•	one ISP
	•	one SIM
	•	one server
	•	one national backbone
	•	one always-on household hub

It depends on the continued existence of people, devices, and movement.

That is much harder to kill completely.

⸻

Architecture sketch

Node roles

A node can be one or more of:

Client
Mostly sends and receives its own mail.

Courier
Carries mail for others.

Post Office
Stable hub. Directory, caching, rendezvous, route summaries.

Bridge
Frequently moves between clusters or networks.

Archive
Preserves public artifacts, directory shards, encyclopedia data.

These are roles, not separate apps.

Core components per node

Identity engine
	•	keys
	•	trust graph
	•	device membership

Bundle store
	•	content-addressed chunks
	•	encrypted payload blobs
	•	retention policies

Routing engine
	•	locality graph
	•	delivery likelihood estimates
	•	path history
	•	custody records

Transport manager
	•	internet direct
	•	relay
	•	LAN
	•	Wi-Fi direct
	•	Bluetooth
	•	manual export/import if needed

Reward engine
	•	verified contribution records
	•	wing minting rules
	•	anti-loop accounting

Policy engine
	•	storage donation cap
	•	battery thresholds
	•	family-first priority
	•	emergency mode

⸻

How routing should think

Do not model routes too literally, like a fragile internet router table.
For Beast Comms, routing is probabilistic and social.

A node should ask:
	•	Is recipient directly reachable now?
	•	If not, which trusted node is most likely to encounter them or their locality?
	•	Which nearby node has best history delivering to that cluster?
	•	Is this worth replicating to 1 node or 3?
	•	Is this emergency traffic?
	•	Is battery or storage scarce?

So route knowledge is more like:
	•	"this courier often reaches village X by evening"
than
	•	"destination IP should go to next hop Y forever."

That is a better fit for intermittent networks.

⸻

Security model

This matters a lot.

Private messages
	•	end-to-end encrypted
	•	relays store ciphertext only
	•	metadata minimized where possible
	•	recipient set may still leak some routing information, so use recipient-group envelopes carefully

Public artifacts
	•	signed
	•	hash-addressed
	•	openly mirrored if user chooses

Trust scopes

Not every node should carry everything.

Users should be able to choose:
	•	family-only forwarding
	•	trusted-community forwarding
	•	public network participation
	•	emergency-only carrying for strangers

That keeps the system socially survivable.

⸻

What can fail without collapse

A good Beast comms design should survive loss of:
	•	one hub
	•	all hubs in a locality
	•	direct internet
	•	DNS
	•	one ISP
	•	SIM service on one carrier
	•	temporary total partition between regions
	•	many devices going offline
	•	duplicate or delayed packets
	•	partially corrupted local caches

If a message exists on several trusted nodes and is content-addressed with signed custody logs, the network can heal.

⸻

Design caution

There are two big traps.

Trap 1: making the routing state too global

A smartphone should not try to know the whole world.
It should know:
	•	itself
	•	its people
	•	its localities
	•	a compressed summary of adjacent route opportunities
	•	a few trusted bridges / hubs
	•	optional DHT shard responsibility if participating deeply

Think federated postal districts, not "global routing table on every phone."

Trap 2: rewarding spam instead of service

If rewards are too naive, people will bounce junk around to farm Wings.

So only reward:
	•	useful delivery
	•	successful custody across meaningful boundaries
	•	participation validated by recipient-side or destination-side evidence
	•	long-duration storage when truly needed
	•	bridge value during real partitions

⸻

One possible Beast wording

You could present the two modes like this:

