v0.3 design. sending out packet through NAT opens temporary port to receive?









Yes. That is the basic intuition.

When a device behind NAT sends a packet out, the NAT typically creates a temporary mapping so return traffic can come back in. That is the opening v0.3 can exploit.

But it is worth stating carefully:

the device does not literally open its own public port.
Its router or carrier NAT creates a temporary translation entry, something like:
	•	internal: 192.168.1.23:51555
	•	external/public: 203.0.113.8:42017

For a short time, packets sent back to 203.0.113.8:42017 may be forwarded to that internal device. That is the basis of UDP hole punching.

So for Beast Comms v0.3, the answer is:

yes, sending outbound traffic often creates a temporary return path through NAT.
That return path can sometimes be used for direct peer-to-peer messaging.

⸻

Beast Comms v0.3

Goal

Extend v0.1 direct messaging with NAT-assisted direct connectivity, so two friends behind home routers or some mobile networks can talk directly more often.

Still text only.
Still no permanent central message hub.
But now we allow a very small amount of peer introduction.

⸻

Key addition in v0.3

Add an introducer / rendezvous service.

This service does not carry messages long-term.
It only helps peers learn:
	•	current public IP
	•	current external port
	•	timing info
	•	whether direct p2p is likely to work

Then both peers send packets to each other at about the same time, trying to create compatible NAT mappings.

This is the classic hole-punch idea.

⸻

Important distinction

There are three different things people often blur together:

1. Outbound connection

You send to a server.
NAT creates temporary mapping.
Server can reply.
Easy.

2. Hole punching

Two peers each send outbound packets, creating mappings.
Then each tries to send directly to the other’s mapped address.
Sometimes works.

3. Port forwarding

User manually configures router.
A stable inbound path exists.
Much more reliable, but worse UX.

For v0.3 you want #2.

⸻

Minimal architecture

Nodes

Each Beast Comms device runs:
	•	identity engine
	•	message queue
	•	local discovery
	•	NAT punching client
	•	direct transport listener

One lightweight introducer

Needed only for coordination.

The introducer keeps very little state:
	•	device public key
	•	current observed public IP
	•	current observed external port
	•	last seen time
	•	maybe NAT behavior hints

It does not store message contents.

So Beast is still mostly p2p.
This is more like a rendezvous helper than a central chat server.

⸻

Basic flow

Let Alice message Bob.

Step 1: Alice and Bob both know the introducer

Each device periodically sends a signed UDP heartbeat to the introducer.

Introducer observes:
	•	Alice appears as 203.0.113.10:40122
	•	Bob appears as 198.51.100.7:55291

Step 2: Alice wants to reach Bob

Alice asks introducer:
	•	do you have a recent route for Bob?

Introducer replies with:
	•	Bob’s public endpoint
	•	last-seen timestamp
	•	maybe NAT type hint if known

Step 3: Bob is notified too

If Bob is online, introducer tells Bob:
	•	Alice wants direct session
	•	here is Alice’s observed endpoint

Step 4: simultaneous punching

Both Alice and Bob start rapidly sending small UDP packets to each other’s observed public endpoint.

This is the "punch."

Their NATs may then allow the inbound packets from each side because each side recently sent outbound traffic.

Step 5: if direct path succeeds

They establish a short-lived secure session and exchange messages directly.

If not, Beast falls back:
	•	queued
	•	retry later
	•	optional relay in future versions

⸻

Why this works

Many NATs behave like this:
	•	outbound packet creates a temporary mapping
	•	replies from the same remote endpoint are allowed back in
	•	sometimes even packets from a newly contacted peer are allowed if timing aligns

So if both peers send packets to each other quickly enough, the NATs may decide:
	•	"this is part of recent outbound traffic"
	•	and let packets through

That is hole punching.

⸻

Why it sometimes fails

Because NATs differ.

Friendly NATs

Often home routers, many consumer setups.
Good chance of success.

Hard NATs

Carrier-grade NAT, symmetric NAT, restrictive enterprise networks.
Much worse.

The hardest case is usually symmetric NAT, where the external port mapping depends on the destination. Then the observed port from the introducer may not match the port used when contacting the peer.

So v0.3 should be designed as:

try punching first, never assume it will work.

⸻

Suggested v0.3 protocol

A. Presence heartbeat to introducer

Sent every so often, maybe every 20–60 seconds while app active.

Contains:
	•	protocol version
	•	user key fingerprint
	•	device key fingerprint
	•	listening UDP port
	•	nonce
	•	timestamp
	•	signature

Introducer records observed:
	•	source IP
	•	source port
	•	freshness

B. Direct-session request

Alice asks introducer for Bob.

Introducer returns:
	•	Bob endpoint candidate(s)
	•	recency
	•	optional NAT success history
	•	Bob’s device fingerprint

C. Punch window

Introducer tells Bob:
	•	Alice is attempting connection now
	•	send punch packets to Alice endpoint for next 10 seconds

Both sides send:
	•	several signed UDP hello packets
	•	repeated bursts for a short window

D. Secure direct hello

If either side receives valid hello:
	•	verify device identity
	•	derive session keys
	•	establish direct encrypted channel

E. Message send

Now send actual text payloads directly.

⸻

Session flow in plain language

Alice taps send.

UI:
	•	Trying direct delivery…
	•	Contacting Bob’s device…
	•	NAT assist in progress…

If it works:
	•	Direct route established
	•	Delivered peer-to-peer

If not:
	•	Bob not directly reachable right now
	•	Message queued for retry

This is honest and still feels good.

⸻

UDP vs TCP

For v0.3, use UDP first.

Why:
	•	UDP hole punching is much more practical
	•	NATs generally handle it better for this use
	•	simpler for direct peer initiation

Then build your secure messaging layer on top of UDP:
	•	reliability for text packets
	•	ack / resend
	•	ordering
	•	duplicate suppression

TCP punching exists, but it is messier and less reliable for a first version.

So the Beast answer is:

v0.3 should do UDP hole punching, not TCP-first.

⸻

Security model

Even with introducer, do not trust the introducer with content.

Introducer can know
	•	who is online
	•	public endpoints
	•	timing
	•	some metadata

Introducer cannot read
	•	message contents
	•	session keys
	•	direct encrypted payloads

Use:
	•	signed device identities
	•	ephemeral session key agreement during direct hello
	•	encrypted text packets afterward

That keeps the introducer small and untrusted.

⸻

State Beast should track per contact

For each friend/device:
	•	last public endpoint observed
	•	last successful direct endpoint
	•	local IP history
	•	MAC history for LAN cases
	•	punch success rate
	•	likely NAT friendliness
	•	last online timestamp from introducer
	•	preferred transport order

So over time Beast learns:
	•	"Bob’s home Wi-Fi usually punches through"
	•	"Bob’s carrier network almost never works"
	•	"when Bob is on village Wi-Fi, direct delivery is easy"

That makes the network feel smarter.

⸻

Retrying strategy

When direct punching fails, do not give up instantly.

Retry on:
	•	recipient comes online
	•	sender network changes
	•	recipient network changes
	•	both seen by introducer within short window
	•	app wake
	•	manual retry

You can also do short punch bursts:
	•	2 seconds aggressive
	•	pause
	•	2 seconds again
	•	maybe a few rounds

Text messaging does not need massive bandwidth, just a reliable little window.

⸻

Local LAN still matters

v0.3 should keep your earlier v0.1 local features.

Best transport order is probably:
	1.	local LAN direct
	2.	known local IP + MAC match
	3.	last successful direct internet endpoint
	4.	introducer-assisted UDP punch
	5.	queue for retry

That gives you the highest value per complexity added.

⸻

UX example

Alice sends Bob:

are you home?

Beast shows:
	•	Checking local routes…
	•	No local route
	•	Bob online via cellular
	•	Attempting direct NAT assist…

Behind the scenes:
	•	introducer gives fresh endpoint
	•	both sides send punch packets
	•	direct hello succeeds
	•	message delivers

UI updates:
	•	Delivered directly
	•	Route: peer-to-peer via NAT assist

If it fails:
	•	Queued
	•	Bob reachable, but direct path failed
	•	Will retry automatically

That phrasing is good because it explains failure without making the system seem broken.

⸻

Hard truth

If you want "replace WhatsApp," v0.3 is a meaningful step, but not enough by itself.

Because some cases will still fail:
	•	both users on hostile carrier NAT
	•	app suspended in background
	•	no simultaneous online overlap
	•	restrictive firewalls
	•	symmetric NAT mismatch

So v0.3 can substantially improve direct reachability, but not guarantee it.

To get closer to WhatsApp reliability you eventually need one or both of:
	•	optional relay fallback
	•	store-and-forward courier nodes

Still, v0.3 is the right next step.

⸻

Tight Beast phrasing

You could define it like this:

Beast Comms v0.3 adds rendezvous and UDP hole punching. Sending a packet outbound causes NAT to create a temporary mapping; Beast coordinates both peers to punch through those temporary mappings and establish a direct encrypted path when possible.

That is the clean version.

⸻

Suggested v0.3 feature list
	•	direct text messaging
	•	local LAN discovery
	•	remembered endpoints
	•	introducer presence heartbeat
	•	introducer-assisted peer rendezvous
	•	UDP hole punching
	•	direct encrypted session after punch
	•	queued retry on failure

⸻

Best mental model

Not:

"sending out opens a port forever"

More like:

"sending out causes the NAT to briefly remember how to send replies back, and if both sides do this in sync, they may be able to talk directly."

That is the right model.

