You’re putting your finger on the real wall.

There is no known elegant, general, guaranteed way for two arbitrary nodes behind arbitrary hostile NATs to establish direct p2p connectivity with no introducer, no relay, no server, and no prior routable path.

That is not a missing trick. It is very close to a constraint of the network model itself.

If both sides are behind NATs or firewalls that reject unsolicited inbound traffic, and neither side has any already-reachable third party, then there is nowhere for the first coordination signal to come from. The packets have no agreed public rendezvous point, no shared externally visible address state, and no way to learn whether the other side is reachable now. In plain terms: the network gives you no handle to grab.

So the hard truth is:

guaranteed p2p across hostile NAT, with zero reachable helper and zero preexisting open path, is not something you can engineer around in the general case.

What you can do is change which weakness you accept.

The mainstream internet chose:
	•	centralized rendezvous
	•	centralized relays
	•	centralized identity
	•	centralized push infrastructure

That buys convenience, but creates exactly the bottlenecks and shutdown points you’re worried about.

If you want to escape that, the design space becomes:

1. Accept non-guaranteed direct p2p
Hole punching, remembered routes, local discovery. Cheap, elegant, but not universal.

2. Accept distributed introducers instead of central ones
Not one company server, but a large rotating set of community-run rendezvous nodes. Harder to shut down, but still some dependency.

3. Accept relay/courier assistance
Not always real-time direct p2p. Sometimes store-and-forward through volunteers, hubs, travelers, local devices. More resilient, less "pure."

4. Accept physical locality as part of the network
Phones meeting phones, villages syncing villages, laptops carrying bundles between partitions. This stops trying to force the internet to do something it was designed to prevent.

That last one is where your thinking becomes unusually strong.

Because the internet’s routing/security model is, in many places, structurally hostile to sovereign p2p. So trying to win purely at the socket level may be the wrong battlefield. If you cannot guarantee path existence, then you design for message survival and eventual movement, not guaranteed instant direct sessions.

In other words:

the elegant answer may not be "better NAT punching."
It may be "stop requiring immediate end-to-end reachability."

That leads naturally to a postal architecture:
	•	direct p2p when available
	•	local LAN sync when possible
	•	opportunistic sync when devices meet
	•	community post offices when they exist
	•	courier forwarding when infrastructure fails
	•	replicated encrypted custody, not central inboxes

Then the weak point is no longer a single server. It becomes a much broader social/physical network of participants. Harder to kill, harder to bottleneck, harder to price-gouge.

So I think your instinct is right, but the target needs to shift slightly:

Not:
	•	"find the guaranteed NAT trick"

But:
	•	"build a communications system whose correctness does not depend on universal direct reachability"

That is a much more promising path.

The fundamental theorem here, in practical terms, is:

If no reachable rendezvous point exists, and no packet can arrive unsolicited, then coordination itself is impossible.

At that point the only remaining resources are:
	•	time
	•	mobility
	•	redundancy
	•	prior trust relationships
	•	previously cached routing knowledge
	•	nearby peers
	•	physically distributed helpers

Which is basically a postal system.

So yes: this is the single biggest problem if you want cheap, resilient, anti-centralized comms. And I do not think the answer is hiding in one more clever NAT trick. I think the answer is architectural: make relaying, couriering, and locality first-class, and make any introducer layer optional, distributed, and disposable rather than central and mandatory.

A useful Beast axiom might be:

#axiom: if a route cannot be guaranteed, the message must still survive

Or even more bluntly:

#axiom: when direct reachability fails, civilization falls back to couriers

If you want, I can draft a Beast Comms architecture for "no guaranteed direct path" as a first principle, where direct p2p is only one transport among many, not the foundation.











