	•	become surveillance points
	•	become points of failure
	•	become tools of control

Whether by design, incentive, or inertia, the result is the same:

direct human-to-human communication is fragile

⸻

The constraint

The network behaves as if it assumes:
	•	endpoints should not be reachable by default
	•	identities should not be stable
	•	addresses should not persist
	•	unsolicited inbound communication should be blocked

Technologies like NAT, dynamic addressing, and restrictive routing create an environment where:

two peers cannot reliably talk without assistance

