⸻

The stance

Beast Comms does not assume a friendly network.

It assumes:
	•	partial connectivity
	•	hostile routing conditions
	•	unstable addressing
	•	intermittent reachability

And it builds anyway.

⸻

Core principle

If direct communication cannot be guaranteed, the system must still deliver the message.

Not instantly.
Not always efficiently.
But reliably over time.

⸻

Beast Comms philosophy

1. Identity over location
People are stable. Addresses are not.
Identity must not depend on IP.

2. Messages over sessions
A session can fail.
A message must survive.

3. Persistence over immediacy
Instant delivery is a luxury.
Eventual delivery is a requirement.

4. Redundancy over fragility
One path fails easily.
Many paths fail rarely.

5. Locality over abstraction
Nearby devices are real.
Global routing is conditional.

6. Participation over dependence
Every node can help move communication forward.

⸻

What Beast Comms builds

A system where:
	•	messages are durable artifacts
	•	delivery is store-and-forward
	•	direct p2p is used when possible
	•	indirect routing is normal, not failure
	•	devices act as couriers
	•	locality is leveraged automatically
	•	infrastructure is optional, not required

⸻

On centralization

Central systems are not evil.
They are simply fragile.

Any system that depends on:
	•	a small number of servers
	•	a small number of providers
	•	a small number of jurisdictions

can be:
	•	shut down
	•	throttled
	•	monitored
	•	manipulated

Beast Comms reduces dependence on such systems.

⸻

On NAT and addressing

Network translation and dynamic addressing create friction for direct communication.

Whether introduced for scaling, policy, or control, the effect is:

direct reachability is the exception, not the default

Beast Comms does not wait for this to change.
It routes around it.

At the same time, it holds a simple position:

stable, globally routable addressing improves human communication

A network where individuals can be reached directly is a stronger network.

⸻

On guarantees

Beast Comms does not promise:
	•	instant delivery
	•	perfect reachability
	•	universal direct connectivity

It promises:
	•	messages will be preserved
	•	delivery will be attempted across all available paths
	•	the system will adapt to network conditions
	•	communication will not depend on a single point of failure

⸻

The model

When two peers can connect directly, they do.

When they cannot:
