Beast Comms

Technical + Philosophical Document (v0.1)

⸻

1. Premise

Communication systems today optimize for immediacy and convenience by concentrating routing, identity, and storage into a small number of intermediaries.

This produces speed and simplicity, but also introduces:
	•	structural fragility
	•	centralized control points
	•	dependency on continuous connectivity
	•	limited direct peer reachability

Beast Comms starts from a different premise:

the network is unreliable, partially reachable, and sometimes adversarial

The system is designed to function within that constraint, not abstract it away.

⸻

2. Core Objective

Enable person-to-person communication that:
	•	does not require a permanent central server
	•	tolerates NAT, dynamic addressing, and intermittent connectivity
	•	preserves messages until delivery is possible
	•	adapts to available transport paths
	•	degrades gracefully instead of failing catastrophically

⸻

3. System Model

3.1 Identity

Philosophy: identity must be stable even when location is not.

Design:
	•	each user has a persistent cryptographic identity (public/private keypair)
	•	each device has its own device key
	•	trust is established explicitly (pairing, QR, shared artifact)

Implication:
	•	routing is decoupled from identity
	•	addresses can change without breaking communication

⸻

3.2 Message as Artifact

Philosophy: sessions are fragile; messages must persist.

Design:
	•	every message is a signed, encrypted artifact
	•	content-addressed (hash-based identity)
	•	stored locally until delivery is confirmed
	•	immutable once created

Properties:
	•	deduplication is trivial
	•	integrity is verifiable
	•	retransmission is safe

⸻

3.3 Delivery Model

Philosophy: delivery is not a single event; it is a process.

Design:
messages move through stages:
	1.	created
	2.	queued
	3.	attempted (direct)
	4.	attempted (assisted)
	5.	stored (intermediate custody)
	6.	delivered
	7.	acknowledged

Implication:
	•	failure at any stage does not destroy the message
	•	delivery is eventual, not guaranteed immediate

⸻

3.4 Transport Abstraction

Philosophy: the system should not depend on a single transport.

Design:
multiple interchangeable transport layers:
	•	local LAN (Wi-Fi)
	•	direct internet (public IP)
	•	NAT-assisted UDP
	•	Bluetooth / proximity (future)
	•	physical transfer (implicit, via device movement)

Implication:
	•	the system routes over what exists, not what is ideal

⸻

3.5 Routing Philosophy

Philosophy: routing is probabilistic and memory-based, not globally authoritative.

Design:
each node maintains:
	•	known endpoints for contacts
	•	last successful routes
	•	locality hints
	•	success/failure history

Routing decisions are based on:
	•	recency
	•	likelihood of success
	•	proximity
	•	trust

Implication:
	•	no global routing table required
	•	network knowledge is partial but improves over time

⸻

3.6 NAT Reality

Philosophy: NAT is a constraint, not a bug to be eliminated.

Design:
	•	attempt direct delivery first
	•	use UDP hole punching when possible
	•	accept that some NATs prevent direct connectivity

Constraint:
	•	no guaranteed direct p2p across all NAT types without coordination

Response:
	•	do not rely solely on direct reachability

⸻

3.7 Store-and-Forward

Philosophy: if a path does not exist now, the message must wait or move differently.

Design:
	•	messages remain in sender custody until acknowledged
	•	optional intermediate custody by trusted nodes
	•	devices may carry messages physically between networks

Implication:
	•	delivery can occur across time, not just space

⸻

3.8 Locality Awareness

Philosophy: nearby devices are often the most reliable path.

Design:
	•	detect known devices via local IP / MAC / signed beacons
	•	prioritize local delivery when available
	•	preload or retain messages relevant to local clusters

Implication:
	•	villages, homes, and communities become natural routing domains

⸻

3.9 Optional Coordination Layer

Philosophy: coordination can exist without central dependency.

Design:
	•	lightweight introducers for NAT coordination (optional)
	•	multiple interchangeable introducers
	•	no message storage in introducers

Implication:
	•	improves connectivity without creating a single point of failure

⸻

4. Failure Model

Beast Comms explicitly defines acceptable failure:

Acceptable:
	•	delayed delivery
	•	multiple delivery attempts
	•	temporary unreachable state
	•	partial network partition

Unacceptable:
	•	silent message loss
	•	irreversible delivery failure
	•	dependence on a single service
	•	global outage from local failure

⸻

5. Security Model

Guarantees:
	•	end-to-end encryption of message content
	•	sender authenticity via signatures
	•	integrity via hashing
	•	replay protection

Tradeoffs (v0.1–v0.3):
	•	metadata visibility at transport layer
	•	no strong anonymity guarantees
	•	NAT introducers may observe presence

Philosophy:
prioritize message integrity and privacy over metadata perfection in early versions.

⸻

6. System Modes

The system adapts to conditions:

Optimistic Mode
	•	direct connections preferred
	•	low redundancy
	•	minimal storage overhead

Partition Mode
	•	increased retries
	•	longer message retention
	•	opportunistic delivery emphasized

Degraded Mode
	•	store-and-forward dominant
	•	local routing prioritized
	•	delivery may depend on movement over time

⸻

7. Resource Model

Storage
	•	message artifacts
	•	routing memory
	•	contact metadata

Bandwidth
	•	small text payloads
	•	retry attempts
	•	optional coordination traffic

Compute
	•	encryption / decryption
	•	signature verification
	•	routing decisions

Philosophy:
keep resource requirements low enough for commodity devices.

⸻

8. UX Principles

1. Honesty
	•	show "queued," "attempting," "delivered"
	•	do not fake real-time guarantees

2. Continuity
	•	messages persist until delivered or expired

3. Transparency
	•	show delivery path when relevant
	•	expose system state without overwhelming

4. Minimal friction
	•	pairing via QR or simple exchange
	•	no complex configuration required

⸻

9. Evolution Path

v0.1
	•	direct messaging
	•	remembered routes
	•	LAN discovery

v0.3
	•	NAT-assisted direct connectivity
	•	optional introducers

v0.4+
	•	relay fallback (optional, distributed)
	•	store-and-forward between nodes
	•	locality-aware caching

long-term
	•	fully opportunistic mesh
	•	artifact-level routing
	•	integration with broader Beast2 systems

⸻

10. Constraints and Limits

Beast Comms acknowledges:
	•	no universal direct connectivity guarantee
	•	dependence on some form of coordination or prior knowledge
	•	tradeoff between efficiency and resilience
	•	increased complexity compared to centralized apps

These are not failures of design.
They are properties of the environment.

⸻

11. Philosophical Position

Beast Comms is not anti-technology.
It is anti-fragility.

It does not reject centralized systems outright.
It refuses to depend on them exclusively.

It accepts:
	•	imperfect conditions
	•	partial connectivity
	•	delayed communication

And still delivers messages.

⸻

12. Axioms

#axiom: identity must survive location

#axiom: messages must outlive the network conditions they are born into

#axiom: if direct paths fail, communication must continue indirectly

#axiom: locality is a first-class routing primitive

#axiom: every node can contribute to delivery

#axiom: if you can’t talk, conflict becomes more likely

⸻

13. Closing

Beast Comms does not attempt to rebuild the internet.

It builds a communication layer that:
	•	tolerates its constraints
	•	reduces its weaknesses
	•	and preserves human connection across failure

It is not perfect.

It is persistent.








