Beast Comms Manifesto (continued)

⸻

The illusion of simplicity

Modern messaging feels simple because complexity is hidden.

You type. You send. It arrives.

Behind that:
	•	identity is abstracted
	•	routing is centralized
	•	delivery is mediated
	•	failure is masked

This creates a fragile equilibrium.

When the center holds, everything feels effortless.
When it breaks, nothing works.

Beast Comms rejects hidden fragility.

It makes the system honest:
	•	delivery may take time
	•	routes may change
	•	connectivity may be partial

But the system itself remains understandable, inspectable, and real.

⸻

The cost of convenience

Centralization compresses complexity into a few systems.

This creates:
	•	operational efficiency
	•	fast iteration
	•	clean user experience

It also creates:
	•	concentration of power
	•	single points of failure
	•	systemic vulnerability

Convenience is not free.
It is paid for with dependency.

Beast Comms shifts that cost:
	•	from central infrastructure
	•	to distributed participation

Not perfectly. Not completely.
But meaningfully.

⸻

Network hostility as a condition

Whether by design, incentive, or emergent behavior, the network often resists direct peer communication.
	•	inbound paths are blocked
	•	addresses change unpredictably
	•	connectivity is asymmetric
	•	reachability is conditional

Beast Comms does not treat this as an anomaly.

It treats it as the baseline.

From that baseline, it asks:

what is the simplest system that still delivers messages under these conditions?

⸻

Delivery as a spectrum

There is no single mode of communication.

There is a spectrum:
	•	instantaneous direct delivery
	•	delayed direct delivery
	•	assisted delivery
	•	cached delivery
	•	carried delivery

Most systems pretend only the first exists.

Beast Comms embraces the full spectrum.

A delayed message is not a failed message.
A carried message is not a degraded message.

It is simply a message moving through a constrained world.

⸻

Time as a resource

Traditional systems optimize for:
	•	latency

Beast Comms also uses:
	•	time

Time allows:
	•	retries
	•	alternative paths
	•	opportunistic connections
	•	human movement

When bandwidth and routing fail, time remains.

⸻

Memory as infrastructure

In centralized systems, infrastructure is external.

In Beast Comms, infrastructure is partially internal:
	•	devices remember routes
	•	devices remember identities
	•	devices remember successful paths
	•	devices remember failures

This accumulated memory:
	•	improves delivery
	•	reduces dependence on discovery
	•	makes the network more effective over time

The network learns because its participants remember.

⸻

Trust as topology

Routing is not only technical.

It is social.
	•	you trust your family
	•	you trust your devices
	•	you may trust your community
	•	you may not trust the broader network

Beast Comms allows routing decisions to reflect that.

Messages can move through:
	•	trusted paths
	•	semi-trusted paths
	•	or minimal exposure paths

Topology is shaped not just by connectivity, but by trust.

⸻

Failure modes

A system should define how it fails.

Beast Comms failure looks like:
	•	delay
	•	partial delivery
	•	eventual arrival
	•	local isolation

It does not look like:
	•	total silence
	•	irreversible loss
	•	centralized outage

Failure is degraded communication, not absent communication.

⸻

Power and shutdown

A centralized system can be:
	•	blocked at a few endpoints
	•	regulated at a few operators
	•	monitored at a few chokepoints

A distributed system must be:
	•	broadly suppressed
	•	continuously disrupted
	•	locally interfered with

This raises the cost of control.

Beast Comms does not make shutdown impossible.
It makes it harder, less precise, and less reliable.

⸻

On addressing and rights

Stable addressing improves:
	•	reachability
	•	predictability
	•	autonomy

A network where individuals can be addressed directly is more aligned with:
	•	peer communication
	•	self-hosting
	•	independence from intermediaries

Beast Comms recognizes this as a desirable property.

It does not depend on it.
But it benefits from it.

⸻

Evolution path

Beast Comms is not built all at once.

It evolves:
	•	direct messaging
	•	remembered routes
	•	opportunistic delivery
	•	assisted connection
	•	distributed routing
	•	courier participation
	•	locality-aware caching

Each step increases resilience.

Each step reduces dependence.

⸻

The role of elegance

The system should not be complex for its own sake.

Elegance in Beast Comms means:
	•	minimal assumptions
	•	composable behaviors
	•	understandable failure
	•	visible state

The goal is not theoretical perfection.

The goal is a system that works under real constraints.

⸻

Human layer

At its core, this is not about packets.

It is about:
	•	families staying in contact
	•	communities coordinating
	•	individuals not being isolated

Technology serves that.

If it fails at that, it does not matter how elegant it is.

⸻

Final axiom

#axiom: messages must outlive the network conditions they are born into

⸻

Closing statement

Beast Comms accepts a constrained, imperfect, sometimes hostile network.

It does not wait for permission.
It does not require ideal conditions.

It builds a system where communication:
	•	persists
	•	adapts
	•	and arrives

Even when the network does not cooperate.































v0.1 beast comms, message delivery with no central hub. each user has list of ips/mac addresses known to be used by friends. goal: replace whatsapp or other centralized services with direct p2p messaging, text only













Here’s a clean v0.1 Beast Comms design for the narrow case:

goal: replace WhatsApp-like centralized text messaging with direct peer-to-peer text delivery, with no central hub, using only information users already know about each other: prior IPs, MAC addresses, and device identity keys.

This version is intentionally modest. It is not "global unstoppable mesh" yet. It is the smallest serious thing that could work.

⸻

Beast Comms v0.1

Scope

What it does
	•	one-to-one text messaging
	•	direct device-to-device delivery when possible
	•	encrypted messages
	•	no permanent central server
	•	offline queueing for later retry
	•	contact list includes known IPs and MACs for friends

What it does not do yet
	•	group chat
	•	media
	•	file transfer
	•	global peer discovery
	•	full NAT traversal
	•	relay network
	•	reputation / wings economy
	•	decentralized identity recovery
	•	multi-device sync beyond simple manual pairing

⸻

Core idea

Every user runs a Beast Comms node on their device.

A node knows:
	•	its own identity keypair
	•	its own local device info
	•	a list of trusted contacts
	•	for each contact, a history of known network coordinates:
	•	local IPs
	•	public IPs previously seen
	•	MAC addresses previously seen on shared local networks
	•	last successful connection times
	•	preferred ports
	•	device public keys

When Alice wants to message Bob, Beast Comms tries all known ways of reaching Bob directly.

It is basically:

trusted address book + encrypted text artifacts + aggressive retry across remembered paths

⸻

Why MAC and IP both matter

IP addresses

Useful for:
	•	direct internet connection if reachable
	•	local LAN connection
	•	reconnecting to a previously reachable device
	•	retrying recent successful paths

Problem:
	•	public IPs change
	•	home NAT hides devices
	•	mobile carrier NAT makes direct inbound hard
	•	local IPs only work on same network

MAC addresses

Useful for:
	•	identifying a known device on the same Wi-Fi/LAN
	•	distinguishing which device is Bob’s when several are nearby
	•	fast local-peer discovery without needing internet

Problem:
	•	MAC addresses do not route across the internet
	•	newer devices may randomize MACs depending on OS/network mode
	•	only helpful on local/shared networks

So in v0.1:
	•	IP is for reaching
	•	MAC is for recognizing nearby devices locally

⸻

Identity model

Each user has a long-lived Beast identity:
	•	user_public_key
	•	user_private_key

Each device also has a device key:
	•	device_public_key
	•	device_private_key

Why both:
	•	user identity stays stable
	•	device identities can be added or revoked later

Each contact entry stores:

contact_name
user_public_key
known_devices[
  device_public_key
  known_public_ips[]
  known_local_ips[]
  known_macs[]
  known_ports[]
  last_seen_at
  last_success_at
]

Messages are encrypted to the recipient user or device key.

⸻

Message model

Each message is a small signed artifact:

message_id
conversation_id
sender_user_key
sender_device_key
recipient_user_key
created_at
sequence_number
ciphertext
signature
ttl
delivery_attempt_count

For v0.1, keep it simple:
	•	text only
	•	UTF-8
	•	max maybe 8 KB per message
	•	one message = one encrypted packet or small bundle

⸻

Delivery flow

Send path

When Alice sends a text to Bob:
	1.	Beast Comms creates encrypted signed message
	2.	stores locally in outbox
	3.	looks up Bob’s known devices and addresses
	4.	tries delivery in this order:

Priority order
	1.	same LAN discovery by MAC / local IP
	2.	last-successful local IP and port
	3.	last-successful public IP and port
	4.	all other recent public IPs
	5.	all other recent local IPs if on matching subnet
	6.	wait and retry later

If one path works:
	•	send message
	•	recipient sends signed ack
	•	sender marks delivered
	•	update Bob’s contact record with successful route

If none work:
	•	message stays queued in outbox
	•	retried later with backoff

⸻

Receiving flow

When Bob’s device receives a connection:
	1.	validate sender device key
	2.	check sender is trusted
	3.	verify signature
	4.	decrypt message
	5.	check for duplicate message_id
	6.	store in inbox
	7.	send signed ack
	8.	update Alice’s last-seen route info

This means each successful exchange makes the address book smarter.

⸻

Local network mode

This is the strongest part of v0.1.

If two friends are on the same Wi-Fi or nearby local network, Beast Comms should work very well.

How

Each device periodically does lightweight local discovery:
	•	listen on fixed UDP port
	•	announce presence with signed beacon
	•	include device key fingerprint, local IP, and optional friendly label
	•	compare seen MAC addresses against trusted contacts

Example:
Alice walks into Bob’s house or village Wi-Fi.

Her app sees:
	•	MAC matches Bob’s known phone
	•	signed beacon from Bob’s device key
	•	local IP 192.168.1.42

Now all queued text messages can deliver directly.

This is simple and strong.

⸻

Direct internet mode

This is weaker, but still worth trying.

If Alice has Bob’s previous public IP and open listening port, Beast can try direct TCP or UDP connection.

This works when:
	•	Bob is on a public IP
	•	or his router forwards the port
	•	or his NAT behavior is favorable
	•	or both are on routable networks

It often fails on mobile networks and many home setups, so v0.1 should treat this as opportunistic, not guaranteed.

⸻

No-central-hub design

"No central hub" means:
	•	no required company server
	•	no required cloud inbox
	•	no permanent broker

But the system can still use:
	•	local persistent storage
	•	remembered peer addresses
	•	direct retry logic
	•	optional manual contact exchange via QR or text blob

That still counts as no central hub.

The hard limit is obvious:
without relay, introducer, or DHT, delivery only works when one peer can directly reach the other using previously known coordinates.

That is okay for v0.1. It is honest.

⸻

Contact exchange

Because there is no global directory, adding a friend should be explicit.

Pairing flow

Alice and Bob meet once in person or over another trusted channel.

They exchange:
	•	user public key
	•	current device public key
	•	current local IP if relevant
	•	current public IP if known
	•	preferred listening port
	•	known device label
	•	optional known MAC addresses for LAN recognition

Best UX:
	•	QR code
	•	copyable contact blob
	•	short invite file

After pairing, they are mutually trusted contacts.

⸻

Storage

For text-only v0.1, storage is tiny.

Each device keeps:
	•	contact list
	•	known routes per contact
	•	message history
	•	undelivered queue
	•	ack history
	•	replay protection cache

Even thousands of messages would be small.

⸻

Retry logic

This matters more than people think.

For each undelivered message:
	•	retry immediately on send
	•	retry when network changes
	•	retry when returning to known Wi-Fi
	•	retry when seeing matching contact beacon
	•	retry on periodic backoff schedule

Example backoff:
	•	0s
	•	10s
	•	30s
	•	2m
	•	10m
	•	1h
	•	6h
	•	daily until TTL expires

Events that should trigger immediate retry:
	•	device wakes
	•	Wi-Fi changes
	•	new public IP detected
	•	local peer discovery sees trusted contact
	•	manual "try now"

⸻

Security model

For v0.1, keep the promise narrow but real.

Guaranteed if implemented properly
	•	message content encrypted end-to-end
	•	sender authenticity via signatures
	•	duplicate/replay detection
	•	no company in the middle reading messages

Not guaranteed
	•	metadata privacy from the network itself
	•	resistance to traffic analysis
	•	anonymity
	•	guaranteed delivery through hostile NATs
	•	forward secrecy unless you add per-message/session ratchets

For v0.1, static identity keys plus signed encrypted messages are enough to start.

⸻

Minimum protocol sketch

1. Discovery beacon

Sent on local network periodically.

Contains:
	•	protocol version
	•	device public key fingerprint
	•	user public key fingerprint
	•	listening port
	•	timestamp
	•	signature

2. Connect hello

When attempting direct connection.

Contains:
	•	sender device key
	•	sender user key
	•	nonce
	•	timestamp
	•	supported protocol version
	•	signature

3. Message packet

Contains:
	•	encrypted message
	•	sender ids
	•	recipient id
	•	sequence number
	•	timestamp
	•	signature

4. Ack packet

Contains:
	•	message_id
	•	recipient device key
	•	timestamp
	•	signature

That is enough for a first implementation.

